<div id="review_3751767085" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3751767085" />
    <a title="Lucia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57640026-lucia"><img alt="Lucia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483569582p2/57640026.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3751767085?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lucia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lucia" href="/user/show/57640026-lucia">Lucia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780316216470" href="/book/show/14781355-the-loved-one">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3751767085" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3998775768040306547"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2120652.Love_the_One_You_re_With' title='Love the One You&apos;re With by Emily Giffin' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Loved One</a> is a cutting satire. Waugh impietiously aims his spotlight on a community of English expatriates in California and on the locals. His prominent tract is a brilliant, pretentiously serious, light-hearted touch, sharp as a knife.<br/><br/>When I think of the clash between the English and the American culture, I am immediately reminded of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45685.The_Canterville_Ghost' title='The Canterville Ghost by Oscar Wilde' rel='nofollow noopener'> The Canterville Ghost</a>, a milestone on this topic. Wilde’s witty humour is light and hiliarious, and preludes to a happy ending. The English and the Americans</span>
  <span id="freeText3998775768040306547" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2120652.Love_the_One_You_re_With" title="Love the One You're With by Emily Giffin" rel="nofollow noopener">The Loved One</a> is a cutting satire. Waugh impietiously aims his spotlight on a community of English expatriates in California and on the locals. His prominent tract is a brilliant, pretentiously serious, light-hearted touch, sharp as a knife.<br /><br />When I think of the clash between the English and the American culture, I am immediately reminded of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45685.The_Canterville_Ghost" title="The Canterville Ghost by Oscar Wilde" rel="nofollow noopener"> The Canterville Ghost</a>, a milestone on this topic. Wilde’s witty humour is light and hiliarious, and preludes to a happy ending. The English and the Americans find a common ground and learn a valuable lesson from each other. <br /><br />Around 60 years later, Waugh’s outlook is definitely pessimistic. The English he depicts have left the old continent (ah the English abroad!) and show off their cultural superiority, playing cricket and disdaining situations that do not match up with their <i>"status"</i>. All that surrounds them in the new continent is veneer and artificiality. The facades in the studios of Hollywood, the funeral homes for pets and humans, the make-up and fake smiles stamped on the corpses, the phrase “the loved one” by which the morticians refer to the dead, the newspaper columnist supposed to give advice …. all this talk about superficiality and expose the money-oriented American mentality.<br /><br />Dennis Barlow, the English protagonist, is no better. He is a failed poet, who plagiarises love poems and eventually gives up his job at the pet cemetery to become a non-sectarian pastor. His vocation is the vocation for money. While poking fun at them, Waugh makes the English and the Americans meet on the common ground of false values. The final scene is emblematic in this sense.<br /><br />Under the surface of dark humour and wry satire, Waugh pens a tragedy on the decline and fall (sounds familiar?) of the English and American cultures.<br /><br /><i>
  <b>“All his (Henry James’s) stories are about the same thing – American innocence and European experience.”<br />“Thinks he can outsmart us, does he?”<br />“James was the innocent American.”<br />“Well, I’ve no time for guys running down their own folks.”<br />“Oh, he doesn’t run them down. The stories all are tragedies one way or another.”</b>
</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="3998775768040306547" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


